{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/2020-10-05-100BooksProject-(10):Inspired-How-to-Create-Tech-Products-Customers-Love/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Joel's dev blog","author":"Joel Mun","siteUrl":"https://9oelm.github.io"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"6d5b53f0-d501-509f-9671-bc657bf0b6b2","excerpt":"Part I: Lessons from top tech companies The author and his team at Hewlett Packard created a state-of-art AI product at a very high price in 1980. Everything…","html":"<h1 id=\"part-i-lessons-from-top-tech-companies\" style=\"position:relative;\">Part I: Lessons from top tech companies<a href=\"#part-i-lessons-from-top-tech-companies\" aria-label=\"part i lessons from top tech companies permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h1>\n<p>The author and his team at Hewlett Packard created a state-of-art AI product at a very high price in 1980. Everything went well, except the fact that <em>no one bought it</em>.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Just one problem: No one bought it (2)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h2 id=\"chapter-1-behind-every-good-product\" style=\"position:relative;\">Chapter 1: behind every good product<a href=\"#chapter-1-behind-every-good-product\" aria-label=\"chapter 1 behind every good product permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Behind every good product, usually there’s someone working tirelessly. (6)</li>\n<li>This book is written for <strong>a product manager</strong>.</li>\n<li>Lots of work for a PM.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"chapter-2-technology-powered-products-and-services\" style=\"position:relative;\">Chapter 2: Technology-powered products and services<a href=\"#chapter-2-technology-powered-products-and-services\" aria-label=\"chapter 2 technology powered products and services permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<p>This book is exclusively for <strong>products powered by tech</strong>, such as:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>e-commerce sites</li>\n<li>social media</li>\n<li>business sites</li>\n<li>mobile apps</li>\n<li>etc</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"chapter-3-getting-to-productmarket-fit\" style=\"position:relative;\">Chapter 3: Getting to product/market fit<a href=\"#chapter-3-getting-to-productmarket-fit\" aria-label=\"chapter 3 getting to productmarket fit permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<p>Three stages of companies (9):</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>startup</p>\n<ul>\n<li>yet to achieve product/market fit</li>\n<li>less than 25 engineers</li>\n<li>PM role is covered by one of the co-founders</li>\n<li>nothing else matters until you find a product that fits the market</li>\n<li>stressful, exhausting, risky, but may be positive and rewarding too (10)</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>growth-stage company</li>\n<li>enterprise company</li>\n</ol>\n<h2 id=\"chapter-4-growth-stage-companies-scaling-to-success\" style=\"position:relative;\">Chapter 4: Growth-stage companies: scaling to success<a href=\"#chapter-4-growth-stage-companies-scaling-to-success\" aria-label=\"chapter 4 growth stage companies scaling to success permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<ul>\n<li>growth-stage companies share one big concern: <strong>how to effectively grow and scale</strong>. (11)</li>\n<li>25 to several hundred engineers</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Common problems:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>product team complains they don’t understand the big picture</li>\n<li>some early methods that led to success are not valid anymore (12)</li>\n<li>technical debt (12)</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"chapter-5-enterprise-companies-consistent-product-innovation\" style=\"position:relative;\">Chapter 5: Enterprise companies: consistent product innovation<a href=\"#chapter-5-enterprise-companies-consistent-product-innovation\" aria-label=\"chapter 5 enterprise companies consistent product innovation permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<p>Common problems (13):</p>\n<ul>\n<li>consistent product innovation</li>\n<li>original vision is achieved, and next vision is obscure</li>\n<li>frustrated leadership with not-innovating product teams</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"chapter-6-the-root-causes-of-failed-product-efforts\" style=\"position:relative;\">Chapter 6: The root causes of failed product efforts<a href=\"#chapter-6-the-root-causes-of-failed-product-efforts\" aria-label=\"chapter 6 the root causes of failed product efforts permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 434px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/4a814cf2326a3887793989a20a5a23ef/57fda/root-causes-of-failed-efforts.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 61.48648648648649%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"root causes of failed efforts\"\n        title=\"root causes of failed efforts\"\n        src=\"/static/4a814cf2326a3887793989a20a5a23ef/57fda/root-causes-of-failed-efforts.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/4a814cf2326a3887793989a20a5a23ef/a80bd/root-causes-of-failed-efforts.jpg 148w,\n/static/4a814cf2326a3887793989a20a5a23ef/1c91a/root-causes-of-failed-efforts.jpg 295w,\n/static/4a814cf2326a3887793989a20a5a23ef/57fda/root-causes-of-failed-efforts.jpg 434w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 434px) 100vw, 434px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Idea to roadmap, roadmap to requirements, … to developing, developing … to deployment. <em><strong>Most companies do it this way.</strong></em></p>\n<p>This is <em>waterfall.</em> (17)</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>While almost everyone today claims to be Agile, what I’ve just described is very much a waterfall process. (17)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3 id=\"details-of-the-problems-1721\" style=\"position:relative;\">Details of the problems (17~21)<a href=\"#details-of-the-problems-1721\" aria-label=\"details of the problems 1721 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Idea</strong>: Sales-driven, stakeholder-driven products. This is often not the best way to pick up on the best idea.</li>\n<li><strong>Biz case</strong>: We <em>can’t know</em> how much money will be earned and spent at the ‘biz case’ stage. <em>Knowing what we can’t know</em> is important.</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Product roadmaps</strong>. It’s got an underlying problem: <em>two inconvenient truths about product</em>.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Half of our ideas are just not going to work</strong>. There is a rare chance customers will keep using the product.</li>\n<li><strong>It’s going to take a long time and several interations</strong> to deliever necessary business value even if the idea works.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li><strong>Project management</strong>: Gathering requirements and documenting them for engineers is more of project management instead of modern product management.</li>\n<li><strong>Design</strong>: It’s too <strong>late</strong> in the game to get the real value of design where every requirement is already set. “Lipstick on the pig” model.</li>\n<li><strong>Engineering</strong>: gets in way too <strong>late</strong> too.</li>\n<li><strong>Agile</strong>: Principles and key benefits of Agile enter the picture far too late</li>\n<li>The entire process is project-centric.</li>\n<li><strong>Customer validation</strong>: happens way too late.</li>\n<li><strong>Huge waste of money and time</strong> being inefficient in the entire process.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2 id=\"chapter-7-beyond-lean-and-agile\" style=\"position:relative;\">Chapter 7: beyond lean and agile<a href=\"#chapter-7-beyond-lean-and-agile\" aria-label=\"chapter 7 beyond lean and agile permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The best product teams often leverage <strong>core principles of Lean and Agile</strong>, but raising the bar on what they’re trying to achieve and how they work. (24)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Three major points on best product team:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Risks are tackled up front</strong>, rather than at the end.</li>\n<li><strong>Collaboration</strong>: Products are defined and design collaboratively, rather than sequentially.</li>\n<li><strong>Solving problems</strong>: It’s all about solving problems, not implementing features.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2 id=\"chapter-8-key-concepts\" style=\"position:relative;\">Chapter 8: Key concepts<a href=\"#chapter-8-key-concepts\" aria-label=\"chapter 8 key concepts permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<p><em>Product</em> in this book is defined holistically. (25) It’s something that includes all of these:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>functions (features)</li>\n<li>tech</li>\n<li>UX design</li>\n<li>monetization</li>\n<li>user and customer acquisition</li>\n<li>offline experiences</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Example: everything eccept the actual merchandise being sold, for an e-commerce site</p>\n<h3 id=\"continuous-discovery-and-delivery\" style=\"position:relative;\">Continuous discovery and delivery<a href=\"#continuous-discovery-and-delivery\" aria-label=\"continuous discovery and delivery permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<p>Two essential high-level activities in all product teams (26~):</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Discover the product to be built</li>\n<li>Deliever that product to the market</li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"product-discovery-27\" style=\"position:relative;\">Product discovery (27)<a href=\"#product-discovery-27\" aria-label=\"product discovery 27 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Will the user buy/use this?</li>\n<li>Can the user figure out how to use this?</li>\n<li>Can our engineers build this?</li>\n<li>Can our stakeholders support this?</li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"prototypes-28\" style=\"position:relative;\">Prototypes (~28)<a href=\"#prototypes-28\" aria-label=\"prototypes 28 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Test many product ideas each week on the order of 10 or 20 per week.</li>\n<li>Meant to be fast and cheap</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"product-delivery-28\" style=\"position:relative;\">Product delivery (28)<a href=\"#product-delivery-28\" aria-label=\"product delivery 28 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<p>Includes:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>scale</li>\n<li>performance</li>\n<li>reliability</li>\n<li>fault tolerance</li>\n<li>security</li>\n<li>privacy</li>\n<li>i18n</li>\n<li>l10n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"products-and-productmarket-fit-28\" style=\"position:relative;\">Products and product/market fit (28)<a href=\"#products-and-productmarket-fit-28\" aria-label=\"products and productmarket fit 28 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<h3 id=\"product-vision-29\" style=\"position:relative;\">Product vision (29)<a href=\"#product-vision-29\" aria-label=\"product vision 29 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<p>long-term objective of the product, for 2-10 years ahead</p>\n<h3 id=\"mvp\" style=\"position:relative;\">MVP<a href=\"#mvp\" aria-label=\"mvp permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Lots of confusions still exist for the term <em>MVP</em>. (29)</li>\n<li><strong>MVP should never be an actual product</strong>: something developers can release with confidence, that your customers can run their business on, …</li>\n<li><strong>MVP should be a prototype.</strong> (30)</li>\n</ul>\n<h1 id=\"part-ii-the-right-people-31\" style=\"position:relative;\">Part II: The right people (31)<a href=\"#part-ii-the-right-people-31\" aria-label=\"part ii the right people 31 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h1>\n<h2 id=\"chapter-9-principles-of-strong-product-teams\" style=\"position:relative;\">Chapter 9: Principles of strong product teams<a href=\"#chapter-9-principles-of-strong-product-teams\" aria-label=\"chapter 9 principles of strong product teams permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<ol>\n<li>Team of missionaries: true believers in the vision, committed to solving problems for the customers.</li>\n<li>Team composition: 10-12 engineers / 1 product manager. </li>\n<li>Team empowerment and accountability: solve hard problems.</li>\n<li>Team size: practical upper bound is 8-12 engineers (two-pizza rule)</li>\n<li>Team reporting structure: usually report to functional manager (designer to head of design, product manager to head of product)</li>\n<li>Team collaboration: product, design, and engineering should work out together.</li>\n<li>Team location: remote works too, but <strong>co-location</strong> is almost always better. Just being together helps. Random chitchats, having lunch together and all that.</li>\n<li>\n<p>Team scope: how do we devide teams if we have many people? Each team may focus on: </p>\n<ul>\n<li>different type of user</li>\n<li>different type of device</li>\n<li>different workflows or customer journey</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Team duration: Keep teams together and stable. It always takes someone a time to gain enough expertise in an area to innovate.</li>\n<li>Team autonomy: we need to give them significant level of autonomy to let them empowered to solve problems.</li>\n</ol>\n<blockquote>\n<p>They are able to try to solve the problems they are assigned in tne best way they see fit.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3 id=\"why-it-works\" style=\"position:relative;\">Why it works<a href=\"#why-it-works\" aria-label=\"why it works permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<p>You basically have to be able to taste the deepest part of the problem and context that customers are facing. This is so far the best way known to do that. (39)</p>\n<h3 id=\"principles-and-techniques\" style=\"position:relative;\">Principles and techniques<a href=\"#principles-and-techniques\" aria-label=\"principles and techniques permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<p>PM has to know what works too, but equally importantly, <em>why.</em> (39)</p>\n<h2 id=\"chapter-10-the-product-manager-41\" style=\"position:relative;\">Chapter 10: The product manager (41)<a href=\"#chapter-10-the-product-manager-41\" aria-label=\"chapter 10 the product manager 41 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<p>Three ways PM could work, but only one works:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>The PM can escalate every issue and decision up to the CEO</li>\n<li>The PM can call a meeting with all the stakeholders in the rom and then let them fight it out</li>\n<li><strong>The PM can do his or her job</strong></li>\n</ol>\n<p>This book tries to convince the third way of working.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The honest truth is that the PM needs to be among the strongest talent in the company. (42)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Many companies disregard the importance of a PM. This book is telling you: <em>please don’t.</em> (42)</p>\n<h3 id=\"key-responsibilities\" style=\"position:relative;\">Key responsibilities<a href=\"#key-responsibilities\" aria-label=\"key responsibilities permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Evaluating opportunities and determining backlog</strong> (what needs to get built) and delivered to customers</li>\n<li>Show evidence that what engineers and designers are asked to build is worth building.</li>\n<li>Manage the product team, whose members build the product for customers.</li>\n</ol>\n<blockquote>\n<p>When a product succeeds, it’s because everyone on the team did what they needed to do. But when a product fails, it’s the product manager’s fault. (43)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3 id=\"deep-knowledge-of-the-customer\" style=\"position:relative;\">Deep knowledge of the customer<a href=\"#deep-knowledge-of-the-customer\" aria-label=\"deep knowledge of the customer permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<p>A PM should know customers’ issues, pains, desires, how they think, … and how product works (43-44)</p>\n<h3 id=\"deep-knowledge-of-the-data\" style=\"position:relative;\">Deep knowledge of the data<a href=\"#deep-knowledge-of-the-data\" aria-label=\"deep knowledge of the data permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<p>Should be comfortable with sales and usage analytics</p>\n<h3 id=\"deep-knowledge-of-your-business\" style=\"position:relative;\">Deep knowledge of your business<a href=\"#deep-knowledge-of-your-business\" aria-label=\"deep knowledge of your business permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Understand your business and how it works, and the role your product plays in your business. (44)</li>\n<li>Understand various stakeholders and constraints (45)</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"deep-knowledge-of-your-market-and-industry\" style=\"position:relative;\">Deep knowledge of your market and industry<a href=\"#deep-knowledge-of-your-market-and-industry\" aria-label=\"deep knowledge of your market and industry permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Understand key trends, customer behaivor, expectations, …</li>\n<li>Understand competitive landscape so that customers may be lured to switch over to your product (45)</li>\n<li>Love technology and tech-powered products.</li>\n<li>Not afraid to learn new tech and constantly changing market</li>\n</ul>\n<blockquote>\n<p>To summarize, deep knowledge 1. of your customer 2. of the data 3. of the business and its stakeholders 4. your market and industry</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3 id=\"smart-creative-consistent\" style=\"position:relative;\">Smart, creative, consistent<a href=\"#smart-creative-consistent\" aria-label=\"smart creative consistent permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<p>These are traits of a successful PM.</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Smart: intellectually curious, quickly learning, and applying new tech to solve problems</li>\n<li>Creative: thinking outside of the normal boundary</li>\n<li>Persistent: constantly pushing the product beyond boundary (47)</li>\n</ol>\n<blockquote>\n<p>PM is not a 9-to-5 job. … there is a ton of work, and it follows you home every night. Pretty much any other role on a product team is better if … work-life balance. (47)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3 id=\"pm-profiles-48\" style=\"position:relative;\">PM profiles (48~)<a href=\"#pm-profiles-48\" aria-label=\"pm profiles 48 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Product management is absolutely distinct from other disciplines</strong>: it’s not a project manager; it’s not a designer. It’s closer to CEO, but PM is not the boss of anyone. </li>\n<li><strong>Like a CEO, the PM must deeply understand all aspects of the business</strong>: just all of the context, from the beginning to the end.</li>\n<li><strong>In every one of these examples, the winning solutions didn’t come from users, customers, or sales</strong>: great product comes from great collaboration between design and engineering to solve real problems (49)</li>\n<li><strong>True leadership is a big part of what separates the great product people from the merely good ones</strong> (50)</li>\n</ol>\n<h3 id=\"pm-vs-po\" style=\"position:relative;\">PM vs PO<a href=\"#pm-vs-po\" aria-label=\"pm vs po permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h3>\n<h1 id=\"reflections-and-applications\" style=\"position:relative;\">Reflections and applications<a href=\"#reflections-and-applications\" aria-label=\"reflections and applications permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h1>\n<h2 id=\"team-duration-38\" style=\"position:relative;\">Team duration (38)<a href=\"#team-duration-38\" aria-label=\"team duration 38 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<h2 id=\"team-autonomy-38\" style=\"position:relative;\">Team autonomy (38)<a href=\"#team-autonomy-38\" aria-label=\"team autonomy 38 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<p>I think this is one of the most difficult toics to handle and apply to the real world setting. </p>\n<h2 id=\"deep-knowledge-of-the-data-44\" style=\"position:relative;\">Deep knowledge of the data (44)<a href=\"#deep-knowledge-of-the-data-44\" aria-label=\"deep knowledge of the data 44 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<p>I should say I’m weak in data analytics. Perhaps I can do enough for excel or python, and at the same time I learn fast; but I never applied my skills for practical stuffs.</p>\n<p>If I want to be a PM at any point in the future, I should really take some introductory courses online.</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-dream-team\" style=\"position:relative;\">The dream team<a href=\"#the-dream-team\" aria-label=\"the dream team permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<p>Everyone’s sharing most traits of PM</p>\n<h2 id=\"the-pm-should-understand-all-aspects-of-the-business-49\" style=\"position:relative;\">The PM should understand all aspects of the business (49)<a href=\"#the-pm-should-understand-all-aspects-of-the-business-49\" aria-label=\"the pm should understand all aspects of the business 49 permalink\" class=\"anchor after\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a></h2>\n<ul>\n<li>This concept just did not directly come into my mind, probably because in my current company the business team is separate from the product team (although this never means that they have no reason to collaborate)</li>\n</ul>","frontmatter":{"title":"100BooksProject: (10): Inspired: How to Create Tech Products Customers Love","date":"October 05, 2020"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/2020-10-05-100BooksProject-(10):Inspired-How-to-Create-Tech-Products-Customers-Love/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/2020-10-04-100BooksProject-(9):Atomic-habits/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"100BooksProject: (9): Atomic habits"}},"next":null}},"staticQueryHashes":["3128451518","426816048"]}